heading.content: Background: How did we get here?

sentences.content: The primary user lost much of her fluency to aphasia.
Even though she lost verbal skills, she is still able to read, albeit slowly and somewhat arduously.
Oral reading of familiar content that contains visual and verbal (written and oral) cues allows her to practice expressing herself with better execution.
The reading companion is a web application (app) originally developed for the primary user.

It presents multimodal personalized content to be read aloud, highlights the current word to be recited and corrects mispronunciations without a human companion through a browser that supports ReactJS and Speech Recognition Web API.

To balance the therapeutic challenge with ongoing self doubt and subsequent frustration, the user is afforded a (configurable) number of retries before the app recites the "stuck" word and advances to the next word.
The app also can recite partial or complete sentences, paragraphs or page.
As primary user worked with her Speech Language Pathologists, additional features have been incorporated based on their recommendations to support word finding and sentence completion.
